[1] Now 119 cases & 23 deaths
Date: Fri 26 Apr 2013
Source: CIDRAP News [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/h7n9/news/apr2613china2br.html


Fujian province cites first H7N9 case as total reaches 119
----------------------------------------------------------
Fujian province today [26 Apr 2013] reported its 1st H7N9 influenza case -- the 9th area of eastern China to be affected by the virus -- as other provinces reported 6 more infections, raising the outbreak total to 119. In a pattern seen throughout the outbreak so far, most of the newly reported cases are in men, and many of the patients are older. The new case from Fujian is in a 65-year-old man who is being treated in a hospital, according to an update today from Hong Kong's Centre for Health Protection. So far none of the man's 24 close contacts have shown symptoms. A resident of Nanchang, the provincial capital, the man is a retiree who hadn't traveled recently and had no contact with poultry, though he lives near a poultry market, according to a report yesterday from the Xinhua, news agency. Fujian is about 485 miles south of Shanghai and borders both Jiangxi province, which reported its first case yesterday, and Zhejiang province, which has reported 45 cases so far, the most of any province.

About 400 laboratories across China have test kits for detecting the virus, so all provinces probably have the capacity to identify cases. Global influenza experts expect cases to continue to rise until the full scope of the virus's source is known. Chinese researchers have linked human illnesses to H7N9 viruses found in market poultry, but questions still remain about other types of exposure and whether other birds or animals harbor the virus.

Other cases reported today include 3 from Jiangsu province. A 49-year-old man is in stable condition, a 36-year-old man is in serious condition, and a 60-year-old man is in critical condition, according to the CHP.

Jiangsu health officials also reported a death from the virus, in a 32-year-old woman whose case was reported earlier this month, according to translated health bureau reports posted on the FluTrackers infectious disease message board. Her death lifts the number of H7N9 fatalities to 23.

China's agriculture ministry said today that tests on samples from poultry farms have found no positive H7N9 samples, Xinhua reported. The ministry said 68 060 samples have been collected so far from poultry markets, habitats, farms, and slaughterhouses across China, but only 46 have tested positive; 44 were from 14 live poultry markets in Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Anhui, and Henan provinces, plus the city of Shanghai. The 2 other positive samples were from Jiangsu and included one from a wild pigeon and another from a household farm of carrier pigeons.

In other developments, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention (China CDC) said yesterday that as of Apr 24 it would update the number of human H7N9 infections every week, which appears to signal an end to daily reports of new cases. Most provincial health departments still appear to be announcing cases as they are confirmed by lab testing.

(By Lisa Schnirring)

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The decision of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention to release weekly updates of cases numbers, rather than daily reports as at present, will help to eliminate confusion and provide a clearer understanding of the course of the outbreak - Mod.CP]

[The positive pigeon farm now turns out to have been for carrier pigeons, not pigeons for consumption. This is a worrying development, because pigeon races are held up to 1000 (one thousand) miles from the home loft. Perhaps a carrier pigeon fancier can tell us if racing pigeons stop on the way home to feed or interact with other pigeons. Beijing has already banned pigeon racing there as a preventive measure, see ProMED archive 20130414.1645731. - Mod.JW]

