[4] Israel MOH guidelines
Date: Sat 27 Apr 2013
From Haaretz Daily, Fri 26 Apr 2013 [in Hebrew, transl Mod.AS, summarised, edited] http://www.haaretz.co.il/news/health/.premium-1.2004491


In view of the spread of A/H7N9 in China, the Director of the Epidemiology Department at Israel's Ministry of Health (MOH), Dr. Emilia Anis, has issued guidelines to the physicians in the Ministry's districts and sub-districts, regarding the detection of suspected cases. "The Ministry of Health monitors the data published in the world and maintains ongoing contact with the relevant parties," says Anis.

It was decided that the preparedness plan will be in line with the measures prepared by the Ministry in relation to the previous avian influenza threat, H5N1, in 2003. This virus strain caused several outbreaks in poultry in Israel during the last decade, but no human cases have been documented in Israel. This is in contrast to neighbouring Egypt, where 168 human cases have been reported, of which 60 died.

According to MOH's definitions, any patient presenting acute, severe respiratory disease signs who had been in China during the 10 days before the onset of symptoms will be regarded as a suspect case of the new virus and be hospitalized under isolation in a biosafety facility (under negative atmpspheric pressure). The Ministry further prescribes medical monitoring of contact persons and family members of such patients , during 10 days following hospitalization.

No limitations on travel to China have been imposed. In line with WHO policy, there is no requirement for medical checks upon those returning from China. However, those travelling to China are advised to maintain strict hygienic measures during their stay (described in some detail), consume well-cooked food and refrain from visiting animal markets, farms and having close contact with animals.

Those returning from China should seek immediate medical advice if they have acute respiratory signs during 10 days after return.

